\subsection{{H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios}\label{sect:h2o}
Following the approach for CO lines from the previous section, we now use the {standard} model grid in Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ovshellmass} to probe the influence of ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}}$ and {$n_{\mathrm{H}_2\mathrm{O}}/n_{\mathrm{H}_2}$\xspace} on the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratio. Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ovshellmass_pars} shows the model grids in which the gas expansion velocity and the dust-to-gas ratio are allowed to vary in addition to the mass-loss rate. Varying the gas expansion velocity implies that changes in ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ are not exclusively due to the mass-loss rate. Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ovshellmass} shows the measured {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios for a cold ortho-{H$_2$O\xspace} transition ($J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=2_{1,2} - 1_{0,1}$ with $E_\mathrm{u} = 114.4$ K) on the left and a warm ortho-{H$_2$O\xspace} transition ($J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=3_{3,0} - 2_{2,1}$ with $E_\mathrm{u} = 410.6$ K) on the right. Additionally, predicted line-strength ratios from the {standard} model grid with adopted parameters given in Table~\ref{table:modelpars} are superimposed on the data points. The observed line-strength ratios span more than two orders of magnitude in {H$_2$O\xspace} vapor abundance. This is the case for all {H$_2$O\xspace} lines in the sample, i.e.~for both cold and warm {H$_2$O\xspace} emission. {For the cold emission line, the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances range from $10^{-6}$ up to $10^{-4}$ for the Mira and SRa sources, and cluster around $10^{-6}$ for the SRb sources with the exception of Y~CVn, which requires an abundance of $\sim 5\times 10^{-6}$. For the warm emission line, the same range of {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances is found for the Mira and SRa sources, while the abundance is an order of magnitude lower for the SRb sources.}

{As discussed in Sect.~\ref{sect:obsh2o}, the model predictions confirm that SRb sources show lower {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances overall. The absolute values should be considered tentatively because the CO line strengths of the SRb sample are not very well reproduced by our chosen model (see Sect.~\ref{sect:cols}), but the difference between the SRb sample and the Mira/SRa sample is large enough to be significant. The tentative upward trend with respect to ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}}$ revealed in Sect.~\ref{sect:obsh2o} is less convincing with respect to ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$, which is really a testament to the small sample size and the uncertainties. Hence, we cannot be conclusive about the trend. In addition, a significantly different abundance for cold and warm {H$_2$O\xspace} is derived for the SRb sample. Such differences are not prominent for the Miras and SRa sources. However, the $J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=3_{3,0} - 2_{2,1}$ {H$_2$O\xspace} transition is formed in the inner wind in SRb stars. As discussed before for the CO lines, our model predictions do not represent the inner wind well, so they are not reliable. The $J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=2_{1,2} - 1_{0,1}$ {H$_2$O\xspace} transition is primarily formed in the intermediate wind, even in SRb stars, so predictions for that line are robust. }

In terms of sensitivity to the assumptions of the {standard} model grid, {only the gas terminal velocity and the dust-to-gas ratio have a noticeable impact on the calculated {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios under the important assumption that our CO line-strength predictions are accurate.} Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ovshellmass_pars} shows {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength-ratio predictions for the {standard} model grid, in which either ${\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ or $\psi$ is allowed to vary. The left panel gives the results for ${\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}} = 10$ {km\,s$^{-1}$\xspace} in black ({standard} model-grid value) and ${\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}} = 25$ {km\,s$^{-1}$\xspace} in green. In the optically thin regime, a change in ${\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$, and therefore in the density tracer ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$, does not substantially affect the {H$_2$O\xspace} emission, as shown by the models for {$n_{\mathrm{H}_2\mathrm{O}}/n_{\mathrm{H}_2}$\xspace} $ = 10^{-7}$. For higher {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances, the lines become optically thick, so that a change in ${\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ affects {H$_2$O\xspace} line strengths significantly. The differences are however well within the uncertainty in the observed line-strength ratios. 

{The right panel in Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ovshellmass_pars} gives the lowest (in red) and highest $\psi$ value (in green) in the grid compared to $\psi = 0.001$ ({standard} model-grid value) in black. The {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength-ratio sensitivity to the dust-to-gas ratio arises because {H$_2$O\xspace} is primarily excited radiatively by IR photons emitted by dust in high-density environments (e.g.,~the right panel of Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ovshellmass_pars} for $\log({\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}) > -7.0$). Here, the higher $\psi$ results in stronger {H$_2$O\xspace} emission, while CO line strengths remain mostly unaffected \citep{lom2013}. In low-density environments, direct stellar light dominates {H$_2$O\xspace} excitation and the sensitivity of {H$_2$O\xspace} line strengths to the dust-to-gas ratio is lost. Again, the differences are well within the uncertainty on the observed line-strength ratios. We conclude that effects of both ${\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ and $\psi$ cannot explain the observed trend in the Miras and SRa sources.}

The comparison between the observed {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios and the theoretical predictions excludes radiative-transfer effects as the sole cause of the downward trend between the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratio and ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$. This confirms that the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratio can be treated as an {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance proxy and that {the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance correlates negatively with the circumstellar density} {in the Miras and SRa sources}. Because the downward trend exists for all {H$_2$O\xspace} transitions regardless of the energy levels involved, {it is the {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanism itself that becomes less efficient with increasing circumstellar density.}

\subsection{{Model reliability}}
{We mention a few caveats regarding the conclusion concerning the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios.} The assumed exponent of the temperature law $\epsilon = 0.4$ has a significant impact on the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios because of its importance for the CO line strength, emphasizing the need to predict the observed CO line strengths accurately. Collisions play a minor role in {H$_2$O\xspace} excitation, so the temperature law does not directly influence the {H$_2$O\xspace} line strengths (e.g.,~\citeauthor{lom2013}~\citeyear{lom2013} for the high-${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}}$ case). {This also corroborates the use of older {H$_2$O\xspace}-H$_2$ collision rates, as discussed in Sect.~\ref{sect:theomodel}.}

Time variability can be an issue in the {H$_2$O\xspace} lines. Recent CW~Leo results derived from \emph{Herschel}-PACS data show variability in {H$_2$O\xspace} line strengths up to 50\% {\citep{cer2014}}. {While CW~Leo shows this for the high-${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}}$ case, a similar behavior may occur at low ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}}$. Assuming 50\% to be the norm, this variability is within the uncertainty on our line-strength ratios. {H$_2$O\xspace} line variability primarily arises from changes in the radiation field, i.e.~in the efficiency of radiative pumping.}

Finally, the predicted {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances are noticeably higher than reported in previous studies for carbon-rich AGB winds, e.g.,~$0.2-0.5\times 10^{-5}$ for V~Cyg \citep{neu2010}, while we predict $1-12\times 10^{-5}$ for the $J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=2_{1,2} - 1_{0,1}$ line and $0.1-1\times 10^{-5}$ for the $J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=3_{3,0} - 2_{2,1}$ line. We must proceed with caution in comparing {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances found here with {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances derived from an in-depth modeling for individual sources. We do not take into account source-specific deviations from the model grid (e.g.,we underestimate the 6.3 {$\mu$m\xspace} flux for V~Cyg specifically; see Fig.~\ref{fig:f63vshellmass}), nor do we consider in-depth all of the available {H$_2$O\xspace} lines for each source. We therefore do not list estimates of {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances for individual sources in our sample. The results presented here serve a different goal: constraining the dependence of the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance on the circumstellar density and, thus, the mass-loss rate. The absolute values may shift up or down somewhat depending on the model assumptions, but the relative difference between sources with different mass-loss rate is robust. In the case of V~Cyg, a higher model prediction for the 6.3 {$\mu$m\xspace} flux would decrease the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance and bring the result more in line with that of \citet{neu2010}. Moreover, \citeauthor{neu2010}~use a significantly higher mass-loss rate. Overall, we arrive at a similar {H$_2$O\xspace} outflow rate as they do.


\section{{H$_2$O\xspace} abundance gradients within single sources}\label{sect:grad}
{In this section, we look for trends in the radial dependence of the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance within individual sources to help constrain the {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanism in carbon-rich winds. To this end, {H$_2$O\xspace} transitions formed in different regions in the wind are compared to trace the radial profile of the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance. A similar strategy was followed by \citet{kho2014}.}
