The major differences between the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profiles occur in the inner wind up to $r \sim 10$ {R$_\star$\xspace}. We would expect to see the most profound effect on lines formed in the inner wind, but this is precisely where our line formation predictions are less reliable. {That does not mean that lines formed primarily outside this zone remain unaffected. The nonlocal nature of radiative pumping implies that a high or low amount of {H$_2$O\xspace} in the inner wind can still affect emission lines formed further out owing to radiative pumping effects. Moreover, a different {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile may shift the line formation regions inward or outward in the wind. It is therefore worth checking how differences in the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile in the intermediate as well as the inner wind affect the line strengths.} Both columns in Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ograd} compare the $J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=2_{1,2} - 1_{0,1}$ line with a line that is formed deeper in the wind, but mostly at radii larger than $\sim 10$ {R$_\star$\xspace}. All in all, the three abundance profiles predict subtle differences in line-strength ratios. We find that, in the case of optically thin lines (e.g.,~for ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}} = 3 \times 10^{-8}$ {$\mathrm{M}_\odot\ \mathrm{yr}^{-1}\ \mathrm{km}^{-1}\ \mathrm{s}$\xspace} and ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}} = 1 \times 10^{-7}$ {$\mathrm{M}_\odot\ \mathrm{yr}^{-1}\ \mathrm{km}^{-1}\ \mathrm{s}$\xspace}, the black and blue curves in Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ograd}), the Decin/Ag\'undez {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile systematically increases the {H$_2$O\xspace}/{H$_2$O\xspace} line-strength ratios with respect to the constant abundance models. This should come as no surprise because the Decin/Ag\'undez {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile results in a {lower} abundance closer to the stellar surface, {which in turn implies that the lines forming deeper in the wind decrease in strength relative to the lines forming further out.} At high ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ the lines saturate and there is no noticeable difference between the constant and Decin/Ag\'undez cases. Compared to the constant abundance profile, the line strengths saturate more quickly for the Cherchneff abundance profile. When reaching representative abundances in the intermediate wind on the order of $10^{-4}$, there is no noticeable difference between different ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ values. 

Comparing the predictions with the measurements, we are immediately confronted with the limitations of the PACS data, which have uncertainties that are too large to distinguish between the different abundance profiles. Nevertheless, the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance is consistently predicted to be on the order of $10^{-6}-10^{-4}$ for the entire ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ range. This range is up to three orders of magnitude larger than what is predicted by \citet{dec2010c} and \citet{agu2010}, as well as by \citet{che2011} for the case of CW~Leo. The measurements for the {H$_2$O\xspace}/{H$_2$O\xspace} line-strength ratio involving the $J_{\mathrm{K}_\mathrm{a}, \mathrm{K}_\mathrm{c}}=2_{2,1} - 2_{1,2}$ line (first column in Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ograd}) tentatively suggest a trend where the ratio increases as ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ decreases (compare the green data points with the blue). {Finally, our results for the Cherchneff abundance profile should not be taken at face value. While the profile for the low {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance value of $10^{-7}$ in the intermediate wind (as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:h2oabun}) is representative of the chemical models calculated for CW~Leo, the high abundance profiles are not. We artificially introduced extremely high abundance values in the inner wind (at $r<3\ \mathrm{R}_\star$) when scaling the profile up or down in representative intermediate-wind abundance. Of course, if we correct for such unreasonably high values, the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile would flatten out and become more similar to the constant {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile. We included the experimental profiles to probe the effect of an increased inner-wind {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance on the {H$_2$O\xspace}/{H$_2$O\xspace} line-strength ratios. They do not represent a realistic view of what a chemical model following \citet{che2011} might look like if it was made to produce higher {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances.}

{It is clear that we have reached the limitations of a grid/sample-based approach. In-depth modeling of individual sources is required to rule out unique differences between observed sources and the model grid. This would allow us to derive further meaningful constraints on the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile.}





