\section{Discussion}\label{sect:disc}
Different {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanisms lead to different properties of the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profile in the wind of carbon stars. In Table~\ref{table:formation}, we summarize these properties for five proposed mechanisms, although most of these predictions are model dependent and have been tailored to explain the {H$_2$O\xspace} observations of CW~Leo, which is the prototypical high mass-loss rate carbon star. Hence a straightforward comparison of predicted values with the {H$_2$O\xspace} observations reported in this study is not feasible, unless the model assumptions of the {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanism agree with the properties of our sample stars. In the table we list the ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ value for which the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance was derived and typical radii and temperatures associated with the formation mechanism. The mechanisms based on the evaporation of icy bodies and radiative association of H$_2$ and O are listed for completeness, but have been firmly ruled out as viable production mechanisms by previous studies \citep{neu2011b,tal2010}. That leaves one mechanism capable of producing {cold} {H$_2$O\xspace} in the intermediate wind from $\sim 15$ R$_\star$ onward, and two mechanisms for producing {warm} {H$_2$O\xspace} in regions closer to the stellar surface. Our observations place four constraints on the {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanism.
\begin{enumerate}
 \item As shown by previous studies for singular sources, and now confirmed to hold for {all} stars in a sample of 18 sources, {H$_2$O\xspace} exists in the inner and intermediate wind. For high mass-loss rate objects, we confirm the presence of {H$_2$O\xspace} at least {as close to the stellar surface as} $\sim$ 10 R$_\star$, just outside the acceleration zone. For low mass-loss rate objects, {H$_2$O\xspace} is present around $\sim 2$ R$_\star$.
 \item {The {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance is in the range of $10^{-6}-10^{-4}$. This is significantly higher than the predictions of state-of-the-art formation mechanisms.}
 \item The {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanism becomes less efficient with increasing mass-loss rate.
 \item {This negative correlation between {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance and mass-loss rate} is observed for mass-loss rates higher than $\sim 5 \times 10^{-7}\ {\mathrm{M}_\odot\ \mathrm{yr}^{-1}}$. The SRb sources in our sample do not follow the trend.
\end{enumerate}
We now discuss properties of {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanisms that so far have not been disproved and relate them to the suggested criteria.

\subsection{Fischer-Tropsch catalysis}
Fischer-Tropsch catalysis allows for a broad range of {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances to be produced by tweaking the Fe-grain number density, but it is unclear how circumstellar column density affects the Fe-grain number density. However, in terms of the other requirements, the Fischer-Tropsch mechanism cannot be reconciled with our observations. Firstly, the presence of warm {H$_2$O\xspace} in the inner wind cannot be explained. Secondly, the mechanism would have to become more efficient at lower wind densities. This is counterintuitive for a mechanism based on dust grains acting as a catalyst because lower densities reduce the amount of interaction between dust and gas that is needed to produce {H$_2$O\xspace}. Thirdly, the mechanism cannot explain the presence of {H$_2$O\xspace} in SRb objects. In these sources, {H$_2$O\xspace} is located close to the stellar surface in too hot of an environment for the mechanism to operate. Even though Fischer-Tropsch catalysis may contribute to {H$_2$O\xspace} formation in carbon-rich environments, it seems very unlikely that it is universally active. Further modeling of this production mechanism for low mass-loss-rate objects needs to be performed to see if it still functions in low-density regions and whether or not it becomes more efficient.

\subsection{UV photodissociation in the inner wind}
\citet{agu2010} have looked into a range of mass-loss rates for the mechanism of UV photodissociation, allowing a comparison with our results. \citet{dec2010c} report results for the same mechanism for CW~Leo. Table~\ref{table:formation} summarizes the results for the different ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ values. In short, the photodissociation mechanism relies heavily on the degree of clumping in the wind for interstellar UV photons to be able to penetrate deeply into the wind. Therefore, the mechanism provides a natural way to explain a broad range of {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances.

The model results shown by \citet{agu2010} also predict a decreasing {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance for objects with high mass-loss rates. This model predicts similar {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances for high and intermediate mass loss, but a sharp increase in {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance for low mass-loss rates. The discontinuity occurs when the major UV-shielded component, i.e.,~the clumps, becomes transparent. Our observations do not show such a sharp increase at a given mass-loss rate, but the model still provides enough flexibility in terms of the clump properties to allow for a more gradual dependence between the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance and ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$. Moreover, once both the UV-shielded and UV-exposed components become optically thin, the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance can be expected to flatten off. This would explain why the SRb sources at ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}} < 5 \times 10^{-7}\ {\mathrm{M}_\odot\ \mathrm{yr}^{-1}}$ do not follow the {negative correlation} between the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratio and the mass-loss rate. {However, the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance toward lower mass-loss rates does not flatten off, and instead decreases (as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:h2ovmdot}). Hence, there appears to be a dependence on the stellar pulsation type, which is difficult to reconcile with this mechanism.}

{We cannot constrain the radial {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance gradient derived by \citet{agu2010} given the uncertainties on the measured line strengths and the low sensitivity of the model predictions to density changes. \citeauthor{agu2010} also predict a maximum abundance of $2\times10^{-7}$ to $10^{-6}$, depending on the mass-loss rate. However, w}e require these profiles to reach a maximum abundance up to three orders of magnitude greater, if they are to explain our {H$_2$O\xspace}/{H$_2$O\xspace} line-strength ratios. There might still be a reasonable degree of flexibility in the formalism to allow for this increase, but this would require further investigation.

The UV-photodissociation scenario suggests that the C$^{17}$O and C$^{18}$O isotopologues also provide atomic oxygen to produce the minor isotopologues {H$_2^{17}$O\xspace} and {H$_2^{18}$O\xspace}, while the main CO isotopologue shields itself from UV radiation. As a result, one expects an isotope-selective enhancement of the {H$_2^{17}$O\xspace} and {H$_2^{18}$O\xspace} abundances with respect to the main {H$_2$O\xspace} isotopologue. Recently, \citet{neu2013} have shown for CW~Leo that this isotope-selective enhancement is less than expected. They suggest that dissociation of C$^{16}$O must contribute a significant number of oxygen atoms as well, if UV photodissociation serves as a basis for {H$_2$O\xspace} formation. {Alternatively, if self-shielding of C$^{16}$O proves to be too efficient, another mechanism that is indiscriminate of CO isotopologues, should contribute to {H$_2$O\xspace} formation in addition to UV photodissociation in the inner wind.}

\subsection{Shock-induced NLTE chemistry}

{As first proposed by \citet{wil1998} and \citet{che2006}, shock-induced} NLTE chemistry provides a universal method to produce {H$_2$O\xspace} in carbon-rich AGB stars: all of them show regular or semiregular pulsational variability, providing the shockwaves that are needed to break up CO and allow {H$_2$O\xspace} to form. {H$_2$O\xspace} is thus expected close to the stellar surface and a dependence on the variability type and pulsation amplitude could be explained in this framework. Important aspects of our {H$_2$O\xspace} analysis concern the similar {H$_2$O\xspace} line strengths between Miras and SRa sources, and the breakdown of the {negative correlation} between the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratio and ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$ at the low end of the range of mass-loss rate that is populated by SRb sources. It could be that SRa sources pulsate in a short-period fundamental mode and SRb sources in a first or second overtone mode. This could affect the shock strengths and densities, which in turn could influence {H$_2$O\xspace} formation. Indeed, \citet{bow1988} found that the overtone pulsational modes experience smaller amplitude shocks. This could lead to a clear differentiation between Miras/SRa sources and SRb sources in terms of {H$_2$O\xspace} formation. Alternatively,{ the lesser regularity of the pulsations, a.k.a.~periodicity,} of SRb sources may also point to instabilities in multiple pulsation modes (e.g.,~\citeauthor{sos2013}~\citeyear{sos2013}), which could result in weaker shocks as well. In contrast, SRa sources are only unstable in one pulsation mode. 


Because \citet{che2011,che2012} has focused on CW\ Leo, a source with a high mass-loss rate that has a period of 650 days, it is difficult to predict how her results would translate to the case of lower or multiple periods. \citet{che2012} states that similar trends can be expected in carbon-rich AGB stars other than CW~Leo. She explains that a lower shock strength can result in a higher {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance due to the complex interplay between the consumption of free oxygen by both {H$_2$O\xspace} and SiO formation processes. As \citet{che2011,che2012} notes, these results rely heavily on the interplay between {H$_2$O\xspace} and SiO production, of which some involved reaction rates are not well constrained. If this process proves viable, it may explain why shorter-period pulsators, and thus lower shock strengths \citep{bow1988}, show higher {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances. {Even though they have a shorter pulsational period, SRb sources instead show lower {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances. However, they also pulsate less regularly. \citet{che2011,che2012} does not consider less regular shocks of lower strength, so it is unclear what their effect would be.}

\citet{che2012} predicts a strong line variability with time for lines formed within $\sim 3$ R$_\star$, i.e.,~where the shocks are strong. {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances can vary several orders of magnitude in this region, and for up to $\sim 80\%$ of one pulsational phase they are significantly higher than at larger distances from the stellar surface {(see also Fig.~\ref{fig:h2oabun})}. Outside this region, {the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance chemically freezes out to its final value over the course of one period, at $\sim 7 \times 10^{-7}$.} As shown in Sect.~\ref{sect:gradmiras} for Mira and SRa sources, we require much larger abundances to explain the observed {H$_2$O\xspace}/{H$_2$O\xspace} line-strength ratios. Hence, the freeze-out over the course of one pulsation phase should occur at much larger abundances instead. It is at this point unclear whether that is possible in \citeauthor{che2011}'s chemical model.

For SRb sources, we cannot draw any firm conclusions owing to the lower reliability of our models in the shocked region. The time variability for lines formed close to the stellar surface could provide an explanation for the erratic behavior of the {H$_2$O\xspace}/{H$_2$O\xspace} line-strength ratios observed in these sources. 

{Interestingly, a shock-induced formation mechanism would not discriminate between isotopologues when breaking up CO. As discussed before when considering {H$_2$O\xspace} formation by interstellar UV photodissociation, additional {H$_2$O\xspace} formation with $^{16}$O is needed \citep{neu2013}. The shock mechanism readily provides this. Additionally, the shock mechanism and the UV photodissociation mechanism both predict significantly lower {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances than required. Therefore, our findings suggest that both mechanisms should contribute to warm {H$_2$O\xspace} formation in carbon-rich environments. Further studies expanding upon the parameter space of both chemical models are required to probe what range of {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances can be produced.}

\section{Conclusions}\label{sect:conc}
We report on new {H$_2$O\xspace} observations made with the PACS instrument onboard the \emph{Herschel} space observatory for a sample of 18 carbon-rich AGB stars in the framework of the MESS guaranteed-time key project (P.I.:~M.~Groenewegen) and an OT2~project (P.I.:~L.~Decin). {H$_2$O\xspace} has been detected in all sample stars, spanning a broad range of mass-loss rates and several variability types. The {H$_2$O\xspace} emission lines include both warm and cold {H$_2$O\xspace} and trace the inner and intermediate wind, providing an unprecedented data set that contributes to solving the issue of {H$_2$O\xspace} formation in carbon-rich environments. We present line-strength measurements for CO, $^{13}$CO, ortho-{H$_2$O\xspace}, and para-{H$_2$O\xspace} between 60 {$\mu$m\xspace} and 190 {$\mu$m\xspace}. 

{For Miras and SRa sources, we find that the observed {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios decrease as a function of the circumstellar density. A comparison of the CO line strengths with a model grid suggests} that a single temperature power law with an exponent $\epsilon = 0.4$ explains all CO observations with a moderate sensitivity to other parameters. As such, CO line measurements can be used as a reliable H$_2$ density tracer. We provide linear fitting coefficients for {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios versus mass-loss rate, which can be used as either a {distance-independent} mass-loss indicator or to predict line-strength ratios if an estimate of the mass-loss rate is available. 

A clear {negative correlation} is evident between the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios and the mass-loss rate for ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}} > 5 \times 10^{-7}\ {\mathrm{M}_\odot\ \mathrm{yr}^{-1}}$, regardless of the upper excitation level of the {H$_2$O\xspace} transitions or the variability type. The low mass-loss-rate SRb sources in our sample deviate from this trend. Only the gas terminal velocity and the dust-to-gas ratio noticeably impact the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratios, but not enough to explain the {negative correlation}. This confirms that the {H$_2$O\xspace}/CO line-strength ratio is a valid distance-independent {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance tracer. As a result, the {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance needed to explain the observed line strengths depends on ${\dot{M}_\mathrm{g}/\varv_{\infty\mathrm{,g}}}$. {When comparing {H$_2$O\xspace}/{H$_2$O\xspace} line-strength ratios with our model grid, we find that the measurements are not sensitive enough to distinguish between different {H$_2$O\xspace} abundance profiles.}

Until now, five {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanisms have been suggested for carbon stars. Three of these mechanisms explain the presence of cold {H$_2$O\xspace} and two predict warm {H$_2$O\xspace} close to the stellar surface. Two cold-{H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanisms have already been ruled out on the basis of previous studies. This leaves a {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanism based on Fischer-Tropsch catalysis on Fe grains in the intermediate wind, and two warm-{H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanisms: one induced by pulsational shocks just outside the stellar surface, and one by photodissociation of molecules such as $^{13}$CO and SiO in the inner wind by interstellar UV photons. {We derive four constraints that must be fulfilled by an {H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanism: 1) warm {H$_2$O\xspace} is present close to or inside the acceleration zone in {all} 18 sources in our sample, 2) {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances are significantly higher than predicted by chemical formation mechanisms, 3) {H$_2$O\xspace} formation becomes less efficient with increasing mass loss regardless of the {H$_2$O\xspace} formation zone, and 4) the {H$_2$O\xspace} properties of the SRb sources are disparate from those of Miras and SRa sources.}

{The Fischer-Tropsch catalysis scenario fails to fully explain up to three of these criteria. Of the two warm-{H$_2$O\xspace} formation mechanisms, shock-induced NLTE chemistry looks the most promising, as the mechanism has the potential to fulfill all formation criteria. A mechanism based on interstellar UV photons cannot easily explain the peculiar behavior of the SRb sources in terms of {H$_2$O\xspace} emission, nor the absence of an isotope-selective enhancement of the {H$_2$O\xspace} isotopologues.}

{Both mechanisms currently fail to predict the high {H$_2$O\xspace} abundances required to reproduce the observed line strengths. This warrants further investigation of the chemical models.}


